Getting the raw data from Gapminder

Go to http://www.gapminder.org/data/. You should see a list of 25 data sets available for download, out of 519 such data sets (as of July 25, 2018). Enter life expectancy in the search box. The second result should be called Life expectancy (years).

Click on the link in the Download column to download an Excel spreadsheet with the data. Open the spreadsheet, which will have several sheets, in Excel. If its not the active sheet already, click on the Data tab to make it active. The first column has a list of countries, and the subsequent columns have life expectancies for years from 1800 through 2016. How are missing values indicated in the spreadsheet?

Although its possible to read Excel spreadsheets directly into R, well first save the spreadsheet as a CSV file. Save it in the working directory of your R session. (If you dont know the working directory, type getwd() in the console window. Ideally youve created a new R project in a directory of your choice, and this will be the working directory.) Excel will probably remind you that it can only save the active sheet, and will also give various other warnings about saving as a CSV file. Choose a simple name such as LifeExp.csv since youll have to use this name as an argument to the read.csv function soon.

Getting the data into R and doing some clean up

Use read.csv to read the data into an object called gapminder1. Make sure to use na.strings to specify how missing data are indicated in the CSV file.

#TODO 8.1: Read in LifeExp.csv and check that it was read in correctly
gapminder1 <- read.csv("LifeExp.csv", header = TRUE, na.strings = "")
dim(gapminder1)
## [1] 260 218

Investigate the data using str, head, names, etc., to make sure it was read in correctly. (Hint: it should have 260 rows and 218 columns.) You dont need to submit code for this, just convince yourself it was read in correctly. Because names in R cannot start with a number, the columns after the first column have an X prepended, e.g., X1804 and X2001. Well address this later on.

The name of the variable containing the countries is something like Life.expectancy (yours might be different, but similar). Rename this column to country. You can do this using the names function.

#TODO 8.2: rename name of the first column to "country"
names(gapminder1)[1] <- "country"

Use apply to compute the mean, median, minimum, and maximum life expectancy for each year. Youll need to exclude the first column, and also will need to tell R how to handle missing values.

Changing the data from wide to long format

Notice the data is in wide format, with each column representing a year rather than long format, where year is a variable.

Load the tidyr library. Use the gather function to transform the data from wide to long format and assign the result back to gapminder1 (i.e., after the call to the gather function, your new gapminder1 should have 56420 rows and 3 columns). Call the variable containing the years year and call the variable containing the life expectancies lifeExp. At this point the years will be represented as X1804 and X2001 for example. We will fix that soon. Consult Section 6.4 of the book for details on the gather function.

#TODO 8.4: Change gapminder1 from wide to long format here
library(tidyr)
gapminder1 <- gather(data = gapminder1, key = year, value = lifeExp, 2:218)
#str(gapminder1)
dim(gapminder1)
## [1] 56420     3

After transformation the data frame should contain 56420 observations (i.e., rows) on 3 variables (i.e., columns).

Because names in R cannot start with a number, the columns after the first have an X prepended, e.g., X1804 and X2001. We will use the substr and as.integer functions to strip off the X and then to convert the resulting values to integer. (The substr function will be covered later in the course, but well use it here anyway!)

First use the code below to strip off the X.

gapminder1$year <- substr(x = gapminder1$year, start = 2, stop = 5)

At that point the variable year should look good, i.e., should have the X removed, but will still be a character vector (see if you can confirm this yourself). Next, use as.integer to convert year to an integer vector.

gapminder1$year <- as.integer(gapminder1$year)

Graphical displays

Load the ggplot2 library and use it to create the following graphical displays:

  1. Draw a histogram of life expectancy, using all the data.
#TODO 8.5: Draw histogram here
library(ggplot2)
ggplot(gapminder1, aes(x = lifeExp)) + geom_histogram()
## `stat_bin()` using `bins = 30`. Pick better value with `binwidth`.
## Warning: Removed 12563 rows containing non-finite values (stat_bin).

  1. Draw side by side boxplots of life expectancy for the years 1900, 1910, 1920, 1930, 1940, 1950, 1960, 1970, 1980, and 1990. Youll probably want to use subset in the data specification of ggplot to obtain only those 10 specific years. Also, try and use the seq function when you subset the data to avoid explicitly creating a vector of these dates.
#TODO 8.6: Draw side boxplots here
typeof(gapminder1$year)
## [1] "integer"
ggplot(gapminder1[gapminder1$year==seq(1900, 1990, by=10),], aes(x = year, y = lifeExp)) + geom_boxplot(aes(group = year))
## Warning: Removed 58 rows containing non-finite values (stat_boxplot).

  1. Draw a line graph of the life expectancy against year for the United States.
##TODO 8.7: Draw line graph here
ggplot(gapminder1[gapminder1$country=="United States",]) + geom_line(aes(x = year, y = lifeExp))

#or
ggplot(subset(gapminder1, country == "United States")) + geom_line(aes(x = year, y = lifeExp))

#or
ggplot(data = subset(gapminder1, country == "United States"), aes(x=year, y=lifeExp)) + geom_line()

names(gapminder1)
## [1] "country" "year"    "lifeExp"
  1. Draw (on the same set of axes) a line graph of life expectancy for the five most populous countries - China, India, United States, Indonesia, and Brazil - where each countrys line is a different color. (Any idea about why life expectancy dropped so much in many of these countries between 1911-1925?)
##TODO 8.8: Draw line graph grouped by country here
ggplot(gapminder1[gapminder1$country %in% c("China","India","United States","Indonesia","Brazil"),]) + geom_line(aes(x = year, y = lifeExp, color=country))
